commit.message: Switch build badge to GitHub actions

CI using GitHub Actions

Some CI is better than no CI. While not as extensive as the origianl Travis CI + Vagrant based CI, this at least will help make sure Violetlands continues to be able to be built on modern machines.

mini-cross based isolated development environment

Since Travis CI is dead and Vagrant is on it's way out, it's time to move on to a docker based development environment.

commit.message: Add "Violetland in action" GIF to README.md

Add demo GIF

The intention here is to add a short gif displaying the game, so that if someone is checking out the project in rush, they can enjoy it before installing. This can be then used in README.md, like in this example project: https://github.com/skishore/inkstone/

When marketing your FLOSS project, IMHO it's important to consider people that will only look at it for a few seconds. Moving images can easily capture your viewer's attention, making them more interested in what else is there. Especially useful if you actually expect your user to build your Ubuntu package on their own.

The video was captured by myself, I license it under WTFPL.

Added shield powerup

added shield powerup with animation, icon and counter
shield animation is on-hit based
added m_sinceLastHitTaken timer to LifeForm class

Bumped CMake requirement to 3.2

CMake 3.2 is required in order to use [FindIntl](https://cmake.org/cmake/help/v3.2/module/FindIntl.html). This also implicitly raises the requirement to Ubuntu 16.04 since Ubuntu 14.04 ships with CMake 2.8.12 by default.

Updated Fedora build instructions

Verified build instructions on Fedora 26 and 27

commit.message:
Fixed Ubuntu build instructions

Initializing git sub modules is strictly required
Fix CMake gettext detection

Fixed Fedora build instructions

Fedora does need a local `gettext` installation in order to build properly. Tested build with Fedora 23, 24 and 25.

Remove #pragma comment directives

Windows binaries are generated by CMake and MXE, thus `#pragma comment`
directives are no longer necessary and only lead to compiler warnings.

Change `LifeForm::MaxSpeed`

Old formula

    max-speed_old(agility) = agility / 5

New formula

    max-speed_new(agility, weight) = 1.5 * agility / (agility * weight + 7.5)

The new formula prevents the speed from increasing too fast while allowing
ridiculously high agilities (see discussion in issue #120).
Reflect AMDmi3's work in CHANGELOG
Do install desktop file and icon
Remove fcitx submodule, use CMake bundled Intl detection module
Use more packaging-friendly license filenames

Honour contributions of Kamil Rytarowski



Kamil Rytarowski added NetBSD support to violetland and maintains the game for that operating system.

Merge pull request #124 from ooxi/patch/file-permissions

Checked all file permissions as requested by issue #113, only `Monster.h` and `Monster.cpp` are executable but should not be.

Merge pull request #130 from krytarowski/netbsd-1

Add NetBSD support
Add NetBSD support

Using `keyserver.ubuntu.com` instead of `keys.gnupg.net`.

@starius [suggested](https://github.com/mxe/mxe/issues/1204#issuecomment-183085017) using `keyserver.ubuntu.com` instead of `keys.gnupg.net` since the former appears to be more stable.

Merge pull request #121 from ooxi/patch/change-Damage

Change `LifeForm::Damage`

--

Old formula

    damage_old(str) = str / 8

New formula

    damage_new(str) = str / (str + 6)

--

The [default strength of a `LifeForm` is one](https://github.com/ooxi/violetland/blob/master/src/game/lifeforms/LifeForm.cpp#L12) and [increases slowly](https://github.com/ooxi/violetland/blob/master/src/windows/CharStatsWindow.cpp#L194).

Merge pull request #117 from ooxi/patch/change-WeaponRetForceMod

Change `LifeForm::WeaponRetForceMod`
Old formula

	wep-ret_old(str) = if   str > 1 → 1 - (str - 1) * 1.1
                       else         → 1

New formula

	wep-ret_new(str) = 1 - ( str - 1 ) / ( str + 1 )

The `WeaponRetForceMod` plays a role in AccuracyDeviation and once you have Strength > 1.9, every weapon is 100% accurate no matter what weapon and how often you fire.

This change thus ensures that weapons never become totally accurate under rapid fire.

Merge pull request #127 from ooxi/feature/readme-preview

Enable local README.md preview

A new Vagrant box is provided, containing an automatic [grip](https://github.com/joeyespo/grip) installation and configuration. This enables local preview of Markdown rendered like GitHub would do.
Updated changelog to include local Markdown preview
